Getting started with the Monitoring API¶

Google Cloud Datalab provides an environment for working with your data. This includes data that is being managed within the Monitoring API. This notebook introduces some of the APIs that Cloud Datalab provides for working with the monitoring data, and allows you to try them out on your own project.

The main focus of this API is to allow you to query timeseries data for your monitored resources. There are also IPython magic commands to help you list the available metrics and resource types.

Notes:

  • Please update the variable PROJECT_ID to point at your own project before executing the notebook. As long as you have at least one GCE instance in your project, the notebook will execute fine.
  • Click on 'Run all Cells' from the dropdown under 'Run' on the top-right to execute this notebook.
  • Always execute the notebook cells in order. Executing out of order can give errors / unexpected results.

Importing the API, and setting the default project¶

The Stackdriver monitoring functionality is contained within the gcp.stackdriver.monitoring module.

If running within datalab, the project within which the datalab VM is running will be the default project. When running locally, the default project is the one set by gcloud config set project.

In [30]:
from gcp.stackdriver import monitoring as gcm

# Update the project ID to run this notebook on your own project.
PROJECT_ID = 'gstackdriver'

Initialize plotly to run in the notebook mode.¶

In [31]:
import plotly.offline as py

Querying timeseries data¶

The gcm.Query class allows users to query and access the monitoring timeseries data. The results of the query can be accessed as a pandas dataframe object. This is a widely used library for data manipulation.

http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/generated/pandas.DataFrame.html

Find all the instance names for a metric.¶

We use the labels_as_dataframe method to get the labels present in a timeseries, and use the metric label 'instance_name' to set up groups based on the names.

In [64]:
q = gcm.Query('compute.googleapis.com/instance/cpu/utilization',
              end_time=datetime.datetime(2016, 5, 3, 23), days=7,
              project_id=PROJECT_ID)

df_labels = q.labels_as_dataframe()

# Extract the instance names and sort them.
instance_names = df_labels['metric.labels']['instance_name'].tolist()
instance_names.sort()

# Create groups based on the prefix before the last '-'
group_to_size = collections.Counter(instance_name.rsplit('-', 1)[0] for instance_name in instance_names)
group_to_size.most_common(5)

df = q.as_dataframe(label='instance_name')

Display the heatmap for the entire dataset¶

The heatmap is interactive - you can zoom into the area of interest, and hover over it to get the data about a cell.

In [38]:
# Intialize the data along the 3 axis of the heatmap.
data = [go.Heatmap(z=df.T.values.tolist(), x=df.index, y=df.columns, colorscale='Viridis')]

# Initialize the figure, and customize the layout to set the left margin, and height.
fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=go.Layout(margin={'l': 120}, height=800))

# Setting the show_link flag to False hides the export link to plotly.
py.iplot(fig, show_link=False)

Select a dataframe of interest.¶

We see above that the usage in packer is very high. Here we zoom into the instances, as well as only look at timestamps from May 1st onwards.

In [47]:
df_packer = df['2016-05-01':].filter(regex='^packer-')
data = [go.Heatmap(z=df_packer.T.values.tolist(), x=df_packer.index, y=df_packer.columns, colorscale='Viridis')]
py.iplot(data, show_link=False)

Find the CPU utilization per group¶

In [39]:
# Create a new dataframe that contains the mean CPU utilization per group.
cpu_per_group = pd.DataFrame()

for group_name, size in sorted(group_to_size.iteritems()):
  if size <= 2:
    continue
  cpu_per_group[group_name] = df.filter(regex=r'^%s-' % group_name).mean(axis=1)
